                <h3 class="title is-4">
                    How to use - Overview
                </h3>
                <p>
                    You can use <strong class="has-text-info">XMLHttpRequest</strong> to call the EpicSevenDB API. The API is configured with CORS, therefore you don't need to worry about Cross-Domain XHR issues. You can also call from your backend if you need, with fetch, curl or any other way you'd prefer.
                </p>
                <div class="notification is-warning">
                    <p><strong class="is-4">Important:</strong></p>
                    <p>
                        This documentation was made when API version was <strong class="has-text-info">0.5.0</strong>. When using it, please access the URL of the route you want to make sure what you expected (and what is presented on this page) is still valid. I'll try keep this page (and this notice) updated.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <p>Scheme:</p>
                <div class="message">
                    <pre class="message-body">https://api.epicsevendb.com/api/<strong class="has-text-info">{:type}</strong>/<strong class="has-text-info">{:?_id}</strong></pre>
                </div>
                <p>
                    Where, for <strong>type</strong>: <br>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Latest Heroes and Artifacts <pre class="message-body">/api/<strong class="has-text-info">latest</strong></pre></li>
                        <li>Hero <pre class="message-body">/api/<strong class="has-text-info">hero</strong></pre></li>
                        <li>Artifact <pre class="message-body">/api/<strong class="has-text-info">artifact</strong></pre></li>
                        <li>Item <pre class="message-body">/api/<strong class="has-text-info">item</strong></pre></li>
                    </ul>
                    The response will ALWAYS contain a <strong class="has-text-info">meta</strong> object containing api version and request date, in case you'd like to cache. Array <strong class="has-text-info">results</strong> with either 0, 1 or more objects will be sent when Route and _id are correct. When the route or _id is wrong, it'll come with extra <strong class="has-text-info">error</strong> and <strong class="has-text-info">stack</strong> properties, pointing the error.
                </p>

